==============================================================================
B. INDUSTRIAL MATERIAL COLORS
==============================================================================
Create clear factory materials before objects and use them consistently:
- Machine painted metal:      (0.55, 0.58, 0.58, 1.0) or off-white/grey
- Dark machine enclosure:     (0.12, 0.14, 0.16, 1.0)
- Stainless/brushed metal:    (0.72, 0.74, 0.76, 1.0)
- Conveyor belt rubber:       (0.03, 0.03, 0.03, 1.0)
- Safety yellow:              (1.0, 0.75, 0.05, 1.0)
- Emergency red:              (0.9, 0.05, 0.03, 1.0)
- Industrial floor concrete:  (0.45, 0.46, 0.44, 1.0)
- Epoxy floor light grey:     (0.62, 0.64, 0.62, 1.0)

Do not use hardwood/fabric/rug materials for factory floors or machines unless
the reference image clearly shows a non-factory object.

==============================================================================
C. COMPOSITE GEOMETRY RULES
==============================================================================

C.0 HARD RULE - DIRECT CREATE CALLS
Do NOT define helper functions for these composites. Emit top-level
`create_box(...)` / `create_cylinder(...)` calls directly inside
`run_layout_engine()` with literal object names. Downstream parsers recognize
literal create calls much more reliably than helper bodies or generated names.

C.1 ENCLOSED MACHINE / CNC
For `structure_hint == "enclosed_machine"` or labels like CNC, machining
center, press, molding machine:
- Use a large base/enclosure box matching the footprint.
- Add a slightly darker front door/window panel as a thin box on the operator
  side when visible.
- Add a control panel box mounted on the front/right side.
- Add small indicator/emergency-stop boxes only if they are attached to the
  machine, not loose tabletop items.
- Keep the machine as a machine; do not substitute wardrobe/cabinet geometry.

C.2 CONVEYOR LINE
For `structure_hint == "conveyor_line"` or labels like conveyor/assembly line:
- Long axis follows the image line direction.
- Emit belt as a long dark thin box at z ~0.9 m.
- Emit frame below belt as metal rails/legs.
- Optional rollers: a few evenly spaced cylinders or narrow boxes, not dozens.
- If a conveyor turns a corner, use separate straight segments with distinct
  names rather than one diagonal blob.

C.3 ROBOT CELL
For `structure_hint == "robot_cell"` or visible robot arm/safety fence:
- Robot pedestal: box/cylinder base at floor.
- Arm: 2-3 cylinders/boxes for links, visually raised above pedestal.
- End effector: small box/cylinder at arm tip.
- Safety fence: thin yellow/grey panels or posts around the cell perimeter,
  leaving a gate/opening if visible.
- Control cabinet: separate cabinet near the cell if Stage 1 lists it.
- Keep all cell pieces inside the room and leave operator/material aisles.

C.4 PALLET RACK / STORAGE RACK
For `structure_hint == "pallet_rack"` or pallet/parts rack labels:
- Use vertical uprights at corners.
- Use horizontal beams/shelves as thin boxes.
- Leave rack interior open; do not make it a single solid cabinet.
- Pallets/bins on the rack may be simple boxes if Stage 1 lists them.

C.5 CONTROL CABINET / ELECTRICAL PANEL
For `structure_hint == "control_cabinet"` or control/electrical cabinet labels:
- Tall thin cabinet body.
- Front door seam/panel as a thin box.
- Small indicator lights/buttons on the front if visible.
- Place against wall or near machine according to Stage 2/image.

C.6 SAFETY FENCE / GUARD RAIL
For `structure_hint == "safety_fence"` or labels like safety fence/guard rail:
- Model as thin posts and rails/panels, not a thick solid wall.
- Height around 1.6-2.0 m.
- Use safety yellow or grey metal.
- Do not block doorways/material paths that are visible in the image.

C.7 WORKBENCH / INSPECTION TABLE
For industrial benches/tables:
- Top slab at z ~0.9 m.
- Metal legs/frame below.
- Do NOT generate loose tools, parts, bins, clipboards, or workpieces as part
  of the bench body. Those are separate small objects handled later.

==============================================================================
D. PLACEMENT RULES
==============================================================================
- Use the reference image as source of truth for positions and long-axis
  orientation.
- Preserve clear aisles. Do not push machines into each other to fill space.
- Wall-side machines/cabinets should touch or nearly touch the wall, with their
  service/operator side facing the aisle.
- Conveyors and assembly lines should align in rows/columns visible in the image.
- Pallet racks usually sit along walls or in parallel rows with wide aisles.
- Safety fences wrap around hazardous machines/robots; they are not decorative
  room partitions.

==============================================================================
E. POST-WRITE CHECKLIST
==============================================================================
Before returning the script:
- Major factory items are not represented as residential furniture.
- Every new object has a material.
- Machine/conveyor/rack dimensions match Stage 1 scale and visible footprint.
